Operation Swath-10 (also known as Bilogora '91){{sfn|Glas Slavonije|3 August 2012}} was planned by the Croatians to regain control of the [[D5 road (Croatia)|Virovitica–Lončarica–Grubišno Polje road]], cutting off and destroying the TO forces deployed in the area of the road (the northernmost part of western Slavonia captured by the TO or the JNA). Those objectives were also designed to deny the Banja Luka Corps support if it attempted to break through towards Virovitica; control the last remaining supply route between Zagreb and Slavonia; shorten the Croatian defensive positions, and improve troop and civilian morale.<ref name=Nazor137>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=137}}</ref> The offensive was originally scheduled for 15 October, but was postponed for two weeks due to the unavailability of the 105th Infantry Brigade and the special police. The plan of operation called for the ZNG to first cut off the two TO battalions on the Bilogora Mountain within 48 hours, with the second stage of the offensive destroying the trapped TO force.<ref name=Nazor1378>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|pp=137–138}}</ref> The operation was authorised by Colonel Miroslav Jezerčić, commander of Bjelovar Operational Zone, on 7 October.<ref name=Nazor136>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=136}}</ref>

The offensive was launched at 6&nbsp;am on 31 October, with a 50-minute [[Barrage (artillery)|artillery bombardment]] followed by a ZNG advance in three groups:<ref name=Nazor136/> the 57th Independent Battalion from the south, the 127th Infantry Brigade from the north and the 1st Battalion of the 127th Infantry Brigade from the northwest.<ref name="Nazor130"/> That day the ZNG captured the villages of [[Velika Barna]], [[Gornja Kovačica]] and [[Zrinska]], northwest of the Grubišno Polje–[[Veliki Grđevac]] road, securing Grubišno Polje. The ZNG also advanced along the Virovitica–Grubišno Polje road, arriving at the outskirts of Mala Peratovica ({{convert|4|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} east of Grubišno Polje) and approaching [[Lončarica]] ({{convert|11|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} south of Virovitica).<ref name=Basic485>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|p=485}}</ref> The TO forces put up a strong resistance (especially near Lončarica), although the battlefield situation was described as hopeless. The TO requested close air support from the Yugoslav Air Force,<ref name=Basic4856>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|pp=485–486}}</ref> and four to six aircraft were deployed in response.<ref name=Nazor138/>

On 1 November the ZNG conducted mopping-up operations in the areas northwest of Grubišno Polje, and the following day the TO force began retreating towards Papuk Mountain. Lončarica and Dapčevački Brđani (a village about {{convert|2|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} northeast of Mala Peratovica, along the Virovitica–Grubišno Polje road) were captured by the Croatian force on 3 November after they overcame strong TO resistance.<ref name=Basic485/> That day, the ZNG was renamed the [[Croatian Army]] (''Hrvatska vojska'', or HV).<ref>{{harvnb|MORH|8 July 2013}}</ref> After the villages were captured, HV forces advancing from Grubišno Polje and Virovitica met; the HV captured the village of Velika Peratovica, which was isolated by the advances along the Virovitica–Grubišno Polje road and northwest of Grubišno Polje on the first day of the offensive. On 4 November the operation was declared finished, after the HV secured the area.<ref name=Basic485/>

==Follow-up operations==
[[File:Map 4 - Croatia - Western Slavonia - September 1991 - January 1992.jpg|thumb|300px|Map showing the fighting in western Slavonia, September 1991 – January 1992; Operation Swath-10 is depicted in the bulge (salient) near the top of the map; Operation Papuk-91, a follow-up to Operation Swath-10, is depicted in the central portion of the map]]

===Battle of Bastajski Brđani===
On 10 November the 57th Independent Battalion advanced against the TO in Veliki Miletinac (east of the area captured in Operation Swath-10), capturing the village the same day. The neighbouring Mali Miletinac was captured by the HV the following day, and on 12 November the HV captured the villages of Bastajski Brđani and Rekići. Two days later the TO counterattacked, killing nine HV troops and wounding about ten more, but the HV defence held. Another effort to recapture Bastajski Brđani was made by the TO, reinforced with 50 paramilitary [[White Eagles (paramilitary)|White Eagles]]. It failed (despite being well prepared and supported by artillery) because the defending HV force was alerted by [[signals intelligence]] of the attack and reinforced. The White Eagles lost 46 killed in the battle.<ref>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=140}}</ref>

===Operation Papuk-91===
Operation Papuk-91 was planned to follow Operation Swath-10, advancing south from the Virovitica–Osijek road and clearing the Papuk and [[Psunj]] mountains of TO forces<ref name=Nazor141/> (elements of the 28th Partisan Division).<ref name=Skvorc119/> The offensive was approved by Jezerčić at a 23 November meeting in Slatina attended by HV [[Inspector General]] [[Martin Špegelj]], Colonel Miljenko Crnjac (commanding officer of the 123rd Infantry Brigade), Colonel Đuro Dečak (commanding officer of the 127th Infantry Brigade), Colonel Josip Černi (commanding officer of the 136th Infantry Brigade) and commanders of other units tasked with its support.<ref name=Nazor141>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=141}}</ref>

The operation was launched on 28 November; the HV advanced across a front spanning Grubišno Polje and [[Orahovica]], nearly {{convert|60|km|abbr=off}} east.<ref name=Nazor141/> On 2 December a detachment of the 123rd Infantry Brigade, en route to relieve troops manning a base on the Papuk, was ambushed with eleven soldiers killed. On 10 December the HV advanced to the Psunj Mountain area north of Nova Gradiška in an offensive, [[codename]]d Gradina, which captured the villages of Šnjegavić, Sinlije, Golobrdac, Vučjak Čečavski, Ruševac, Jeminovac, Čečavac and Opršinac. The advance improved the safety of the Nova Gradiška–[[Požega, Croatia|Požega]] road and secured the right flank of the Nova Gradiška axis of Operation Hurricane-91.<ref name=Nazor145>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=145}}</ref>

From 12 to 15 December the HV captured a cluster of villages around [[Đulovac]], southeast of the area captured in Operation Swath-10. The HV units approaching from the east captured [[Voćin]], about {{convert|10|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} southeast of Đulovac, on 14–15 December.<ref name=Nazor145/> Voćin and Đulovac were badly damaged by the retreating TO and paramilitary White Eagles,<ref>{{harvnb|Duijzings|2000|pp=54–55}}</ref> and the latter killed [[Voćin massacre|43 civilians in Voćin]] on 13 December.<ref>{{harvnb|Duijzings|2000|p=55}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|ICTY|15 January 2003|p=6}}</ref> The victims' bodies were mutilated and left unburied, presumably as a warning to others.<ref>{{harvnb|Gow|2003|p=163}}</ref>

On 16 December the HV (in an operation codenamed Sokolina) captured the villages of [[Gornji Vrhovci]], [[Kamenski Vučjak]] and Kamenski Šušnjari, about {{convert|15|km|abbr=off}} south of Voćin and {{convert|10|km|abbr=off}} west of [[Velika, Croatia|Velika]]; this restricted the TO forces to the southwestern slopes of Papuk Mountain and Psunj Mountain further south. The following day, the HV captured [[Novo Zvečevo]] and a TO supply depot in the village (halfway between Voćin and Kamenski Vučjak) in an attack codenamed Johanesberg.<ref name=Nazor145/> On 18 December the HV advanced southwest from Kamenski Vučjak (in an advance codenamed Laništa), capturing the villages of [[Striježevica]], Bogdašić, Amatovci and Kamenski Šeovci and coming within {{convert|1|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} of the village of Kamenska (on the Pakrac–Požega road). Over the following three days, the HV performed mopping-up operations in the area.<ref name=Nazor146>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=146}}</ref>

On 21 December, the HV launched an unsuccessful attack (codenamed Prkos) on Kamenska and the adjacent village of [[Mijači]]. The TO withdrew from the area north of Kamenska (including the village of Sažije on 24 December), retreating from Kamenska and Mijači the next day. HV forces deployed in the Pakrac area (west of the Papuk and the Psunj), advanced east to support Operation Papuk-91 (capturing the villages of [[Dereza, Požega-Slavonia County|Dereza]], Gornji Grahovljani, Donji Grahovljani, [[Kusonje]] and [[Španovica]] on 24–25 December) and left less than {{convert|15|km|abbr=off}} of the Pakrac–Požega road  separating HV units advancing from the west and east.<ref name=Nazor146/> Operation Papuk-91 ended on 26 December, when forces of the 123rd, the 127th and the 136th Brigades met at [[Bučje, Pakrac|Bučje]]; the final day's advance was codenamed Velebit.<ref>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|pp=146–147}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
Five HV soldiers were killed in the operation and dozens were wounded.<ref>{{harvnb|Večernji list|1 November 2014}}</ref> Twenty-four JNA personnel and Croatian Serb rebels were also killed, as were 22 Serb civilians. A further 17 Serb civilians were killed in the weeks preceding the operation,<ref>{{harvnb|Srna|30 October 2013}}</ref> in which Croatian forces secured {{convert|370|km2|abbr=off}} of western Slavonia (including 21 villages). Although the HV secured the Virovitica–Grubišno Polje road, it failed to trap the TO troops deployed to the area. This was later attributed to insufficient manpower: the unavailability of the 105th Infantry Brigade or the 73rd Independent ([[Garešnica]]) Battalion, which were deployed in Pakrac. The HV positions set the stage for further advances against the [[SAO Western Slavonia]] in Operation Papuk-91.<ref name=Nazor139>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=139}}</ref> Some sources conflate Operations Swath-10 and Papuk-91, describing the latter as part of Operation Swath-10.<ref>{{harvnb|Thomas|Mikulan|2006|p=50}}</ref> Operation Papuk-91 eliminated the threat to the road connecting eastern Slavonia and Zagreb; the TO forces were pushed south, placing the road out of artillery range.<ref>{{harvnb|Štefančić|2011|p=428}}</ref> In Operation Papuk-91, the HV captured 110 settlements<ref name=Nazor141/> and {{convert|1230|km2|abbr=off}} of territory.<ref name=Nazor130>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=130}}</ref>

In 2008, a monument to HV troops participating in the offensive was unveiled in Grubišno Polje.<ref>{{harvnb|Virovitica.net|4 November 2008}}</ref> Another monument was erected on Papuk Mountain to the 11 soldiers from the 123rd Infantry Brigade who were ambushed in Operation Papuk-91 on 2 December 1991.<ref>{{harvnb|034portal.hr|2 December 2011}}</ref> Operations Swath-10, Papuk-91 and Hurricane-91 (implemented in western Slavonia in late 1991) are considered the first offensive liberation operations in the Croatian War of Independence.<ref>{{harvnb|MORH|2011|p=11}}</ref>

The [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY) charged [[Vojislav Šešelj]] with a number of [[war crime]]s, including the killings by the paramilitary White Eagles in Voćin on 13 December. Although the trial ended in 2012, {{as of|2013|August|lc=yes}} the verdict was pending.<ref>{{harvnb|Jutarnji list|20 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|30 August 2013}}</ref> [[Slobodan Milošević]], president of Serbia at the time of the killings, was also charged by the ICTY for the crimes in Voćin; however, Milošević died before his trial ended.<ref>{{harvnb|ICTY IT-02-54|p=1}}</ref>

===Refugees===
About 4,000 [[Croatian Serb]] civilians fled the area affected by Operation Swath-10.<ref>{{harvnb|Srna|30 October 2013}}</ref> According to Serbian sources, the population began to evacuate on the first day of the offensive; by the second day, about 800 vehicles had entered [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. The retreating columns included men of military age who refused to fight.<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|p=486}}</ref> A substantial number of refugees settled in [[Baranja]], in houses owned by displaced [[Croat]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|pp=491–492}}</ref> Based on reports of fleeing civilians, the [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] government accused Croatia of [[ethnic cleansing]] and other civil-rights violations. Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandar Mitrović wrote to the [[European Community Monitor Mission]] (ECMM), accusing Croatia of personal and property damage and the displacement of Serb civilians. Although the accusations were countered by evacuation plans made by SAO Western Slavonia authorities on 25 October<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|p=487}}</ref> and the testimony of civilians remaining in the area (that the TO ordered the population to flee, claiming that "the [[Ustaše]] are coming&nbsp;[...] and killing every Serb"),<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|p=488}}</ref> Serbian media [[Role of the media in the Yugoslav wars|extensively reported alleged atrocities]]. Reports compared the Croatian offensive to the [[World War II]] [[List of massacres in the Independent State of Croatia|massacres committed by the Independent State of Croatia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|p=489}}</ref> On 3 November the [[Presidency of Yugoslavia]] condemned the offensive, citing the destruction of 18 Serb villages, and the following day the [[National Assembly (Serbia)|National Assembly]] of Serbia appealed to the international community for help.<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|pp=489–490}}</ref>

In response to the situation (and a request from the Presidency of Yugoslavia) an ECMM team toured the area affected by the offensive on 6 November, targeting locations where media reports indicated atrocities; these included Velika Peratovica, Mala Peratovica, Gornja Rašenica, Donja Rašenica and Lončarica. The 6 November ECMM report refuted the accusations; although the team found only one Serb couple remaining in the area, they denied claims that the HV mistreated civilians left behind. The ECMM team reported no systematic destruction of houses, although a number of structures had artillery-bombardment damage and a small number of houses, farms and [[haystack]]s were recently torched. The team was unable to determine if the HV was to blame, if the villagers avenged SAO Western Krajina leaders or if the destruction was a result of a [[scorched earth]] policy by the retreating force.<ref>{{harvnb|Bašić|Miškulin|2010|p=490}}</ref>

The HV offensives in western Slavonia conducted in late 1991 (Operations Hurricane-10, Swath-10 and Papuk-91) created a total of 20,000 Serb refugees. They fled the area when the JNA ordered Croatian Serb forces to withdraw,<ref>{{harvnb|HRW|13 February 1992|loc=note 28}}</ref> and were settled in the JNA-held Baranja region of eastern Croatia.<ref>{{harvnb|HRW|21 January 1992|p=297}}</ref> The refugee resettlement coincided with Croatian Serb efforts to change the ethnic composition of the [[Danube]] area seized in late 1991, providing a secondary motive for the expulsion of non-Serb civilians.{{sfn|The New York Times|10 May 1992}}

===Ceasefire===
{{main|Vance plan}}
A 3 January 1992 ceasefire allowed the implementation of the [[Vance plan]], which protected civilians in areas designated as [[United Nations Protected Area (UNPROFOR)|UN Protected Areas]] (UNPAs) and deployed UN peacekeepers in Croatia.<ref>{{harvnb|Armatta|2010|pp=194–196}}</ref> One of the UNPAs defined by the plan, UNPA Western Slavonia, encompassed parts of the municipalities of Novska and Nova Gradiška and all of Daruvar, Grubišno Polje and Pakrac. This UNPA covered the area held by the JNA on 3 January, additional territory to the north (recaptured by the HV in late 1991) and towns never under SAO Western Slavonia control (such as Grubišno Polje and Daruvar).<ref>{{harvnb|Ramcharan|1997|pp=449–450}}</ref> The peacekeeping force ([[United Nations Protection Force]], or UNPROFOR), initially expected to be 10,000-strong,<ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=106}}</ref> began its deployment on 8 March.<ref>{{harvnb|Trbovich|2008|p=300}}</ref>

